context: Some researchers believe that the first Russian settlement in Alaska was established in the <a0_0><b4_0><b5_0>17th century<b5_0/><b4_0/><a0_0/>. According to this hypothesis, in 1648 several koches of <a1_0><b6_0>Semyon Dezhnyov<b6_0/><a1_0/>'s expedition came ashore in Alaska by storm and founded this settlement. This hypothesis is based on the testimony of Chukchi geographer Nikolai Daurkin, who had visited Alaska in <a3_0><b8_0>1764–1765<b8_0/><a3_0/> and who had reported on a village on the Kheuveren River, populated by <a2_0><b7_0>"bearded men" who "pray to the icons"<b7_0/><a2_0/>. Some modern researchers associate Kheuveren with Koyuk River.
